      <mainheadword>
         <syriac>
            <rtl intref="#g140d2b09-88de-42b4-becb-6998df37c87e">ܐܰܢ̱ܬܬܳܐ</rtl>
         </syriac>
      </mainheadword>
      <sedra-id>11191</sedra-id>
      <gender-inflection>f</gender-inflection>
      <etymaramaicbefore>For Syr and T the protoform can be reconstructed as *<italics>ˀattaṯā</italics> (with a subsequent metathesis in T), while the forms attested in other Aramaic idioms, both ancient and modern, point to <italics>i</italics> in the first syllable, i.e., *ˀ<italics>ittaṯā</italics>. For the plural there are also two main possibilities: *<italics>niššīn</italics> (Syr, CPA, T) and *<italics>nVšīn</italics> (*<italics>našīn</italics>?), cf. <italics>nəšīn</italics> in JPA, JBA, TO. In NENA (CU, B, JNA, JNAB) Arm *ˀ<italics>ittaṯā</italics> was ousted by a new term <italics>baxta</italics> with unclear etymology  [DCU 101, DNAB 1243, JNAD 110, DB 337]. While Mutzafi [DB 337] suggests a back-formation from <italics>bāḵtāṯā</italics> ‘female spinners’, cf. Syr <syriac>
            <rtl>ܒܟܟܬܐ</rtl>
         </syriac>, CAL proposes a semantic shift from a term for “hen”, cf. Syr <syriac>
            <rtl>ܒܟܬܐ</rtl>
         </syriac>. </etymaramaicbefore>
      <etymsemiticbefore>To PS *<italics>ˀanṯ-at</italics>- ‘woman’ [GCS 44]. The phonetic development lying behind MSA forms is unclear. The suppletive plural forms in Hbr, Arm and Arb go back to PCS *<italics>nVš-ūma</italics> ‘women’, a semantic narrowing of an original meaning ‘people’, cf. Akk <italics>nišū</italics> and Ugr <italics>nšm</italics> [GCS 195].</etymsemiticbefore>
